    <section id="new-diagnosis" class="content-section content-urgent">
      <div class="urgent-box">
        <h2>💙 Just received a diagnosis?</h2>
        <p>Take a breath. CKD is serious, but it's manageable — often for years. The most important thing right now is not panicking. Here's what matters most in the first week:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Get your cat eating</strong> — this is the most urgent priority. It doesn't have to be a kidney diet. It just has to be food.</li>
          <li><strong>Get a phosphorus number</strong> from the bloodwork. If your vet hasn't discussed it, ask specifically.</li>
          <li><strong>Ask about an IRIS stage</strong> — this gives you a framework for understanding where your cat is.</li>
          <li><strong>Don't change everything at once.</strong> Abrupt diet changes in a sick cat can make things worse.</li>
        </ul>
        <a href="#diet" class="btn btn-primary btn-sm">Read: My Cat Won't Eat →</a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="what-is-ckd" class="content-section">
      <h2>What is Chronic Kidney Disease?</h2>
      <p>Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) — also called Chronic Renal Failure (CRF) or Chronic Kidney Insufficiency (CKI) — is a progressive, irreversible reduction in kidney function. The kidneys lose their ability to filter waste from the blood, regulate fluids, and produce certain hormones.</p>
      <p>It is extremely common in senior cats. Some estimates suggest that over a third of cats over age 12 have some degree of CKD. The good news: with appropriate management, many cats live comfortably for years after diagnosis.</p>
      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>The key insight from Bruce:</strong> CKD management is not about returning the kidneys to normal. It's about slowing progression, managing symptoms, and keeping your cat comfortable and eating. Those are different goals — and they change how you evaluate every treatment decision.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="iris-staging" class="content-section">
      <h2>IRIS Staging — What Stage Is Your Cat?</h2>
      <p>The International Renal Interest Society (IRIS) staging system is the standard framework vets use to categorize CKD severity. It's based primarily on creatinine levels, with sub-staging for blood pressure and protein in the urine.</p>

      <div class="iris-grid">
        <div class="iris-stage iris-1">
          <div class="iris-num">I</div>
          <div class="iris-label">Minimal loss</div>
          <div class="iris-creat">Creatinine &lt; 140 µmol/L</div>
          <p>Early disease. Often no symptoms. Detected by SDMA, urinalysis, or imaging. Best time to start management.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="iris-stage iris-2">
          <div class="iris-num">II</div>
          <div class="iris-label">Mild CKD</div>
          <div class="iris-creat">140–250 µmol/L</div>
          <p>Mild symptoms may appear — increased thirst, weight changes. Most cats are diagnosed here. Excellent prognosis with management.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="iris-stage iris-3">
          <div class="iris-num">III</div>
          <div class="iris-label">Moderate CKD</div>
          <div class="iris-creat">251–440 µmol/L</div>
          <p>More noticeable symptoms. Nausea, appetite changes, weight loss. Treatment becomes more active. Quality of life focus intensifies.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="iris-stage iris-4">
          <div class="iris-num">IV</div>
          <div class="iris-label">Severe CKD</div>
          <div class="iris-creat">&gt; 440 µmol/L</div>
          <p>Significant symptoms. Comfort and quality of life are the primary goals. Supportive care rather than aggressive intervention.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="content-callout content-callout--amber">
        <strong>Important:</strong> IRIS staging is a guide, not a verdict. Many cats live well beyond what their stage might suggest. Staging should inform treatment decisions — not replace your knowledge of your individual cat.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="lab-results" class="content-section">
      <h2>Understanding Lab Results</h2>
      <p>Your vet will monitor several key values over time. Here's what matters and what to watch for — in plain language.</p>

      <div class="labs-table">
        <div class="lab-row lab-header">
          <span>Marker</span>
          <span>What it measures</span>
          <span>What to watch for</span>
        </div>
        <div class="lab-row">
          <span><strong>Creatinine</strong></span>
          <span>Primary kidney function marker — waste product filtered by kidneys</span>
          <span>Rising trend over time. Single readings are less important than the trend.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="lab-row">
          <span><strong>BUN</strong></span>
          <span>Blood urea nitrogen — another waste product. Affected by diet and hydration.</span>
          <span>High BUN with high creatinine = kidney origin. High BUN with normal creatinine = often dietary.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="lab-row">
          <span><strong>SDMA</strong></span>
          <span>Early kidney function marker — detects loss before creatinine rises</span>
          <span>Can detect CKD when 25–40% of function is lost. Ask for this if it's not included.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="lab-row lab-highlight">
          <span><strong>Phosphorus</strong></span>
          <span>Mineral the damaged kidney cannot clear properly</span>
          <span>Elevated phosphorus accelerates kidney disease. This is the most actionable number. See below.</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="phosphorus" class="content-section">
      <h2>Phosphorus — The Number Your Vet May Underemphasise</h2>
      <p>If there's one piece of information Bruce's years gave us, it's this: <strong>phosphorus management is the most important dietary intervention in CKD.</strong></p>
      <p>Damaged kidneys cannot clear phosphorus efficiently. Elevated phosphorus accelerates kidney damage — it's a vicious cycle. Restricting dietary phosphorus is one of the most evidence-backed interventions available, yet it's often under-discussed at the vet appointment.</p>

      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>Ask your vet specifically:</strong> "What is my cat's phosphorus level, and what is our target range?" If they don't have a specific target, push for one. The IRIS recommendation is &lt; 1.45 mmol/L for Stage 2, &lt; 1.61 mmol/L for Stage 3.
      </div>

      <p>Phosphorus restriction comes from diet first (wet food generally has less than dry), and then from phosphorus binders if diet alone isn't enough. More on both in the diet and medications sections.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="diet" class="content-section">
      <h2>Diet & Food — Including "My Cat Won't Eat"</h2>
      <p>Appetite loss is extremely common in CKD cats, caused primarily by nausea from toxin buildup (uraemia). This is the most urgent issue in the first days after diagnosis.</p>

      <div class="content-callout content-callout--urgent">
        <strong>The rule we learned from Bruce:</strong> Food in the cat is always the priority. A cat who refuses the kidney diet but eats their regular food should eat their regular food. Starvation damages the liver and accelerates decline far faster than slightly elevated phosphorus.
      </div>

      <h3>The kidney diet debate</h3>
      <p>Prescription kidney diets are formulated to be low in phosphorus and protein. The evidence for their benefit — particularly phosphorus restriction — is solid. But they are only beneficial if your cat will eat them. A prescription diet sitting uneaten helps no one.</p>
      <p>Our approach: introduce kidney food gradually, mixed with whatever your cat will currently eat. Some cats transition willingly. Some never do. For the ones who won't, focus on phosphorus control through binders and high-moisture food.</p>

      <h3>Wet food over dry</h3>
      <p>Hydration is critical for CKD cats — damaged kidneys cannot concentrate urine effectively, leading to dehydration. Wet food significantly increases water intake. If your cat is on dry food, transitioning to wet is one of the most impactful changes you can make.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="fluids" class="content-section">
      <h2>Sub-Cutaneous Fluids</h2>
      <p>Sub-Q fluids — fluids given under the skin, absorbed into the body — are one of the most effective tools for managing CKD. They compensate for the kidneys' inability to concentrate urine, reduce toxin buildup, and often produce a dramatic improvement in how a cat feels.</p>
      <p>Many cat owners give sub-Q fluids at home. It sounds intimidating and becomes routine within a few sessions. If your vet hasn't discussed this, ask: <em>"Is my cat a candidate for home sub-Q fluids?"</em></p>
      <p class="content-coming-soon">📋 Detailed sub-Q fluids guide — coming soon, including equipment list and technique.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="medications" class="content-section">
      <h2>Medications</h2>
      <p>There are several medications commonly used in CKD management. Your vet may or may not have discussed all of them — the vet toolkit has a list of questions to ask.</p>

      <div class="meds-list">
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Phosphorus binders</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Bind phosphorus in the gut before it's absorbed. Options include aluminium hydroxide, calcium carbonate, and newer options like Epakitin. Critical if dietary restriction alone isn't controlling phosphorus.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Anti-nausea medication</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Maropitant (Cerenia), ondansetron, or metoclopramide. Often dramatically improves appetite in cats suffering from uraemic nausea.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Appetite stimulants</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Mirtazapine (also has anti-nausea properties) or capromorelin (Elura). Can be transformative for cats who have stopped eating.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">ACE inhibitors / Telmisartan</div>
          <div class="med-desc">For cats with protein in the urine or hypertension. Reduce pressure on the kidneys and can slow progression.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="content-callout">
        If your cat has stopped eating and your vet hasn't discussed anti-nausea medication, ask directly: "Has uraemic nausea been ruled out as the cause of appetite loss? Should we try anti-nausea medication?"
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="quality-of-life" class="content-section">
      <h2>Quality of Life Over Lab Numbers</h2>
      <p>This is the philosophy at the core of this site, and it came directly from Bruce. CKD management can become an obsession with numbers — chasing creatinine targets, panicking over phosphorus spikes, restricting diet aggressively. But your cat doesn't know their creatinine level. They know whether they feel well enough to eat, to play, to curl up in the sun.</p>
      <p>The signs that matter more than the bloodwork:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Is your cat eating willingly?</li>
        <li>Are they grooming themselves?</li>
        <li>Do they seek out interaction and comfort?</li>
        <li>Are they having more good days than bad?</li>
      </ul>
      <p>A cat with elevated creatinine who is eating well, engaged, and comfortable is doing better than a cat with lower creatinine who refuses food and hides. Don't let the numbers tell you the opposite of what your cat's behaviour is telling you.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="vet-conversations" class="content-section">
      <h2>Conversations to Have with Your Vet</h2>
      <p>These are the questions that changed outcomes for us — the ones too many owners don't know to ask.</p>

      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li>What is my cat's IRIS stage, and what does that mean for treatment?</li>
        <li>What is the phosphorus level, and what is our specific target?</li>
        <li>Has uraemic nausea been considered as the cause of appetite loss?</li>
        <li>Is my cat a candidate for home sub-Q fluids?</li>
        <li>Are we managing blood pressure? Has it been tested recently?</li>
        <li>What are we optimising for — longevity, quality of life, or both?</li>
        <li>What would you change if this were your cat?</li>
      </ul>

